   "source": [
    "Using multiple forecasting loss functions and inference latency was crucial in identifying practical strengths and weaknesses of each approach. Under RMSE-based evaluation, XGBoost achieved the highest number of stock wins (31/112), followed by Random Forest (17/112) and Decision Tree (11/112). Under QLIKE, XGBoost again led with 55/112 wins, while LASSO (30/112) and GJR-GARCH(1,1) (22/112) ranked second and third, respectively. This divergence reflects the fundamentally different behaviour of the two metrics. RMSE penalises large absolute errors symmetrically, while QLIKE penalises under prediction of volatility more heavily, making it better aligned with the asymmetric risk associated with under predicting volatility.\n",
    "\n",
    "Mean inference latency reveals significant separation between model classes. Lightweight models such as HAR-RV (0.044 μs), LASSO (0.227 μs), Ridge Regression (0.231 μs), and Decision Tree (0.295 μs) operate at sub-microsecond speeds. XGBoost (0.719 μs) remains fast despite its ensemble complexity. In contrast, GARCH-family models are substantially more expensive, with GARCH(1,1) and GJR-GARCH(1,1) being approximately 700 times slower than XGBoost. Given that latency arbitrage races typically resolve within 5-10 μs (Aquilina et al., 2021), these differences significantly impact real-time trading applications.\n",
    "\n",
    "XGBoost has both the lowest average QLIKE loss and the most wins across stocks, with 55 wins and the lowest mean QLIKE loss of 0.496. This is followed closely by LASSO with 30 wins and mean QLIKE loss of 0.518, and trailed farther behind by GJR-GARCH(1,1) with 22 wins, though worse tail performance in QLIKE loss increases its mean QLIKE loss to 0.596. No other models win on more than 2 stocks, though we note consistent performance from the Random Forest, decision tree, and linear regression models."
   ]
