   "source": [
    "@fig-pareto-frontier shows the Pareto frontier of QLIKE loss against inference latency. The Pareto-optimal set consists of HAR-RV, LASSO, and XGBoost, where no alternative achieves simultaneously lower prediction error and lower latency. HAR-RV occupies the low latency extreme, XGBoost has the lowest QLIKE loss and LASSO provides an intermediate between the two. All remaining models are dominated, meaning at least one Pareto-optimal alternative performs better. Overall, we find a tradeoff between inference latency and accuracy. While XGBoost has the best overall balance between computational efficiency and predictive performance, our Pareto analysis supports that no single model is universally optimal across all evaluation criteria. Hence, model selection should depend on traders' latency tolerance and accuracy requirements.\n",
    "\n",
    "## Part B: Deployment process\n",
    "\n",
    "The final product is deployed as an interactive Streamlit web application, organised into three pages accessible through a fixed top navigation bar: a Model Specification page, an Individual Stock page, and a Universe page for cross-stock comparisons. To keep the tool responsive, all model results are pre-computed and cached during an initial backend run lasting between thirty minutes and four hours depending on models selected and available hardware. Once cached, results load instantly, with the specific backend run displayed to the user to ensure traceability. @fig-individual-stock-widget illustrates the Individual Stock page, where the user selects a stock and time_id to view observed realised volatility alongside forecasts from every model for the final thirty seconds. A clearly marked forecast start line separates the observed period from the forecast horizon, with held-out realised volatility overlaid for direct visual assessment.\n",
    "\n",
    "From a data science perspective, the individual stock view lets a practitioner diagnose where models fail at a granular level, for example, whether a fast linear model like LASSO tracked a volatility spike as closely as XGBoost, or whether GARCH predictions diverged during periods of rapid order book activity. Aggregate win counts and average QLIKE scores alone obscure this stock level and window level variation. From a trader's perspective, this granularity matters because a model which performs well on average may still behave poorly on the specific assets in a trader's portfolio. By surfacing both the universe-level Pareto frontier and per stock diagnostic detail in a single interface, the dashboard gives traders the high-level model selection guidance and the asset specific insight needed to deploy a volatility model with confidence. Give the demo a try yourself below."
   ]
